        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top' nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>MadMac</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>***** This thread is off-topic, if you aren't interested in reading about RL government issues, skip ahead. *****</P><P>You are right, a Republic is not a Democracy.  Late night of driving from LA will cloud the brain a bit.  Is what I should have said was 'Xell is mostly right', in that a Republic is more similar to a Democracy than it is to a Communist government.</P><P>A Republic and a Democracy have some similarities, but have some very important differences.  For what it is worth, the US is not a Democracy, but a Republic.</P><P>A few quotes from those that can do a better job than I of explaining:</P><P>"Our Republic was founded upon the principles of Liberty (the right to do whatever one wishes so long as those actions do not infringe upon the equal rights of others) and limited government, not democracy. In fact, seldom if ever will one see reference to democracy in the founding documents of our nation, at least in a positive context. "  - <a href="http://www.deoxy.org/demorep.htm" target="_blank">http://www.deoxy.org/demorep.htm</a></P><P>"Alexander Hamilton was aware of this tendency of a democratic form of government to be torn apart by itself, and he has been quoted as writing: "We are now forming a republican form of government. Real liberty is not found in the extremes of democracy, but in moderate governments. If we incline too much to democracy, we shall soon shoot into a monarchy (or some other form of dictatorship.)" - <a href="http://www.deoxy.org/demorep.htm" target="_blank">http://www.deoxy.org/demorep.htm</a></P><P>"Our nation was founded as a constitutionally limited republic, as any grammar school child knew just a few decades ago (remember the Pledge of Allegiance: "and to the Republic for which it stands"...?). The Founding Fathers were concerned with liberty, not democracy. In fact, the word democracy does not appear in the Declaration of Independence or the Constitution. On the contrary, Article IV, section 4 of the Constitution is quite clear: "The United States shall guarantee to every state in this Union a Republican Form of Government (emphasis added). The emphasis on democracy in our modern political discourse has no historical or constitutional basis." - <a href="http://www.house.gov/paul/tst/tst2000/tst121200.htm" target="_blank">http://www.house.gov/paul/tst/tst2000/tst121200.htm</a></P><P><BR>"Republic isn't a democracy. People's REPUBLIC of China, Soviet Socialist REPUBLIC...it just means a group of individuals, a congress/parliament, runs the country." - Potus</P><P>Here is Webster.com definition of a Republic:<BR>Main Entry: re·pub·lic <BR>Function: noun<BR>1 a (1) : a government having a chief of state who is not a monarch and who in modern times is usually a president (2) : a political unit (as a nation) having such a form of government b (1) : a government in which supreme power resides in a body of citizens entitled to vote and is exercised by elected officers and representatives responsible to them and governing according to law (2) : a political unit (as a nation) having such a form of government c : a usually specified republican government of a political unit</P><P>The Ukraine has three main branches of government; Executive, Legislative, and Judicial.  They have a Constitution, and universal suffrage at the age of 18.  Their Legislative branch is currently made up of:</P><P>“Legislative branch: unicameral Supreme Council or Verkhovna Rada (450 seats; under Ukraine's new election law, half of the Rada's seats are allocated on a proportional basis to those parties that gain 4% of the national electoral vote; the other 225 members are elected by popular vote in single-mandate constituencies; all serve four-year terms) <BR>elections: last held 29 March 1998 (next to be held NA 2002) <BR>election results: percent of vote by party (for parties clearing 4% hurdle on 29 March 1998) - Communist 24.7%, Rukh (combined) 9.4%, Socialist/Peasant 8.6%, Green 5.3%, People's Democratic Party 5.0%, Hromada 4.7%, Progressive Socialist 4.0%, United Social Democratic Party 4.0%; seats by faction (as of 25 February 2000) - Communist 115, PRVU 36, Fatherland Party 35, United Social Democratic 34, People's Democratic Party 27, Trudova Ukrayina 27, Rukh (K) 27, left-center 23, Green 18, Rukh (U) 17, Peasant Party 15, Hromada 14, Reforms Congress 12, independents 14, unaffiliated 31, vacant 5 “ - <a href="http://www.odci.gov/cia/publications/factbook/geos/up.html#Govt" target="_blank">http://www.odci.gov/cia/publications/factbook/geos/up.html#Govt</a></P><P>Sounds like they have all the beginnings of a solid Republic government.</P><P>Leonid Kuchma was elected President by the people of his country.  Was it a fair election?  Is the parliament ruled by communist hard line stooges?  Honestly I don’t know, as I have never been let alone lived in the Ukraine.  Keep in mind that you can not change a country, it’s culture and politics in ten years, let alone in overnight.  Do you think that the US was the same ten years after our independence as it is now?  I doubt it.  Also, it is very possible that many of the countries that are calling themselves a Republic, are not one in the strictest definition of the word.  Maybe they want to look uber ;)</P><P>"Yeah, we have trouble counting millions of votes, not determining whether we want to murder our own citizens or let the people think for themselves." - Potus</P><P>As one of the few 1st world countries that still allows capital punishment, many people in this world would say that the US does determine whether we want to "murder" one of it's citizens.  Until 1865, millions of people were killed and enslaved due to the color of their skin, and until 1920 women in this country could not vote.  Many people think that one of the primary reasons for the creation of the Electoral College was infact to "protect" the country from having the uneducated, uninformed, ignorant people of the late 18th century from picking the President of our country.</P><P>***** RL discussion over *****</P><P>Ok, back to the bickering about the 59th level pet.</P><P><BR> </font></td>
